<DOC><DOCNO> AP890731-0126 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-89 2030EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-AgricultureArrests     07-31 0295</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Agriculture Arrests,280</SECOND><HEAD>USDA Says 18 Indicted on Tobacco-Related Charges</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Agriculture Department said Monday that 18people have been indicted on tobacco-related charges, ranging fromconspiracy to false identification of tobacco, and federal agentshave started making arrests in the cases.   The indictments, charging a total of 138 violations, stemmedfrom a two-year investigation involving tobacco warehouse ownerswho were accused of falsely identifying and marketing tobacco byusing illegally acquired marketing cards, USDA Deputy InspectorGeneral Leon Snead said in a statement.   ``One warehouse owner was charged with using illegally obtainedmarketing cards and his tobacco dealer card to sell excess tobaccothat he had purchased illegally from tobacco producers or stolenfrom the warehouse floor,'' he said.   The arrests Monday were made by agents of the USDA's office ofinspector general, the U.S. Marshals Service and Internal RevenueService.   If convicted, the defendants could face fines of up to $10,000and five years imprisonment on each count. They also could faceUSDA administrative penalties.   According to the USDA, the federal indictments were againstGlenn S. Martin Jr., 41, tobacco dealer and owner of Big BurleyTobacco Warehouse, Johnson City, Tenn.; Graham Cole, 55, Moultrie,Ga., tobacco dealer and owner of Planters Brick Tobacco Warehouse,Pelham, Ga., and Peachtree Tobacco Co., Moultrie, Ga.   Gordon Cox, 53, Billy Crain, 27, Jimmy Fender, 36, Fred A. King,37, Bruno Guillen, 25, Mark Dawson, 26, Kenneth Dawson, 28, all ofJohnson City, Tenn.; Robert Nelson, 54, Kenneth Roberts, 42, bothof Jonesboro, Tenn.; Kenneth Meredith, 55, Elizabethton, Tenn.;Alan Myers, 31, Charlotte's Courthouse, Va.   Johnny Shelton, 42, Mars Hills, N.C.; Howard Cantrell, 47,Erwin, Tenn.; Raven Stuart Wright, 33, Appomattox, Va., MaxceyBrown, 49, Mullins, S.C., and Ernest Copeland, 44, Byrdstown, Tenn.</TEXT></DOC>